Discriminated unions are the cleanest approach when the conditional field is a type/method selector. Use `.superRefine()` when conditions are more complex (checkbox toggles, numeric thresholds). For forms, use `useWatch` to reactively show/hide fields based on the discriminator value.

Reusable refinement functions for validation rules that go beyond basic type checking.

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

// Phone number validation (international)
const phone = z.string().refine(
  val => /^\+?[1-9]\d{6,14}$/.test(val.replace(/[\s-()]/g, '')),
  'Invalid phone number. Include country code (e.g., +1234567890)'
);

// URL slug
const slug = z.string()
  .min(2).max(100)
  .regex(/^[a-z0-9]+(?:-[a-z0-9]+)*$/, 'Slug can only contain lowercase letters, numbers, and hyphens');

// Credit card (Luhn algorithm)
const creditCard = z.string().regex(/^\d{13,19}$/).refine(num => {
  let sum = 0;
  let alternate = false;
  for (let i = num.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    let n = parseInt(num[i]);
    if (alternate) { n *= 2; if (n > 9) n -= 9; }
    sum += n;
    alternate = !alternate;
  }
  return sum % 10 === 0;
}, 'Invalid credit card number');

// Strong password (with specific requirements)
const strongPassword = z.string()
  .min(8, 'At least 8 characters')
  .superRefine((val, ctx) => {
    const checks = [
      { test: /[A-Z]/, message: 'uppercase letter' },
      { test: /[a-z]/, message: 'lowercase letter' },
      { test: /[0-9]/, message: 'number' },
      { test: /[^A-Za-z0-9]/, message: 'special character' },
    ];
    const missing = checks.filter(c => !c.test.test(val)).map(c => c.message);
    if (missing.length > 0) {
      ctx.addIssue({
        code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom,
        message: `Must contain: ${missing.join(', ')}`,
      });
    }
  });

// Date range validation
const dateRange = z.object({
  start: z.string().datetime(),
  end: z.string().datetime(),
}).refine(
  data => new Date(data.end) > new Date(data.start),
  { message: 'End date must be after start date', path: ['end'] }
);

// Hex color
const hexColor = z.string().regex(/^#[0-9a-fA-F]{6}$/, 'Must be a hex color (e.g., #FF5500)');

// IP address
const ipAddress = z.string().ip({ message: 'Invalid IP address' }); // Zod built-in!

// Semantic version
const semver = z.string().regex(
  /^(0|[1-9]\d*)\.(0|[1-9]\d*)\.(0|[1-9]\d*)(-[a-zA-Z0-9.]+)?(\+[a-zA-Z0-9.]+)?$/,
  'Must be a valid semver (e.g., 1.2.3)'
);
```

Extract common validations into reusable schemas. Name them descriptively and include format examples in error messages. Test edge cases (empty strings, boundary values, unicode) for each custom refinement.

tRPC uses Zod natively for input/output validation with full type inference.

```typescript
import { initTRPC, TRPCError } from '@trpc/server';
import { z } from 'zod';

const t = initTRPC.context<{ userId?: string }>().create();

const publicProcedure = t.procedure;
const authedProcedure = t.procedure.use(({ ctx, next }) => {
  if (!ctx.userId) throw new TRPCError({ code: 'UNAUTHORIZED' });
  return next({ ctx: { userId: ctx.userId } });
});

export const appRouter = t.router({
  user: t.router({
    // Zod validates input automatically
    getById: publicProcedure
      .input(z.object({ id: z.string().uuid() }))
      .query(async ({ input }) => {
        // input.id is string (UUID validated)
        return db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: input.id } });
      }),

    update: authedProcedure
      .input(z.object({
        name: z.string().min(2).max(100).optional(),
        email: z.string().email().optional(),
        bio: z.string().max(500).optional(),
      }))
      // Output validation ensures response shape
      .output(z.object({
        id: z.string(),
        name: z.string(),
        email: z.string(),
        bio: z.string().nullable(),
      }))
      .mutation(async ({ input, ctx }) => {
        return db.user.update({
          where: { id: ctx.userId },
          data: input,
        });
      }),

    list: publicProcedure
      .input(z.object({
        cursor: z.string().optional(),
        limit: z.number().min(1).max(100).default(20),
        search: z.string().max(100).optional(),
      }))
      .query(async ({ input }) => {
        const users = await db.user.findMany({
          take: input.limit + 1,
          ...(input.cursor && { cursor: { id: input.cursor }, skip: 1 }),
          ...(input.search && {
            where: { name: { contains: input.search, mode: 'insensitive' } },
          }),
        });
        const hasMore = users.length > input.limit;
        return {
          users: hasMore ? users.slice(0, -1) : users,
          nextCursor: hasMore ? users[input.limit - 1].id : null,
        };
      }),
  }),
});

export type AppRouter = typeof appRouter;

// Client — fully typed, Zod errors become tRPC errors
const user = await trpc.user.getById.query({ id: '...' });
const updated = await trpc.user.update.mutate({ name: 'New Name' });
// TypeScript knows exact shapes without any codegen
```

tRPC + Zod gives you: automatic input validation (returns 400 on invalid input), full TypeScript type inference on the client, output validation to prevent leaking internal fields, and per-procedure middleware (auth, rate limiting).

Four popular TypeScript validation libraries with different design philosophies.

```typescript
// Zod — most popular, great DX
import { z } from 'zod';
const schema = z.object({ name: z.string().min(2), age: z.number().int() });
type User = z.infer<typeof schema>;

// Yup — older, widely used with Formik
import * as yup from 'yup';
const schema = yup.object({ name: yup.string().min(2).required(), age: yup.number().integer().required() });
type User = yup.InferType<typeof schema>;

// Valibot — smallest bundle, tree-shakable
import * as v from 'valibot';
const schema = v.object({ name: v.pipe(v.string(), v.minLength(2)), age: v.pipe(v.number(), v.integer()) });
type User = v.InferOutput<typeof schema>;

// ArkType — fastest runtime, TypeScript-native syntax
import { type } from 'arktype';
const schema = type({ name: 'string > 1', age: 'integer' });
type User = typeof schema.infer;
```

| Feature | Zod | Yup | Valibot | ArkType |
|---------|-----|-----|---------|----------|
| Bundle size | ~14KB | ~15KB | ~1-3KB (tree-shaken) | ~8KB |
| Type inference | Excellent | Good | Excellent | Excellent |
| Performance | Fast | Moderate | Fast | Fastest |
| Tree-shaking | Partial | No | Full | Partial |
| Ecosystem | Largest | Large (Formik) | Growing | Small |
| API style | Chainable | Chainable | Pipe-based | Template literal |
| Form integration | RHF, Formik | Formik (native) | RHF, Formik | Limited |
| Error messages | Customizable | Customizable | Customizable | Built-in |

**Choose Zod** for: best overall DX, largest ecosystem, most community schemas. **Choose Yup** for: existing Formik projects, migration cost is too high. **Choose Valibot** for: bundle-size-critical apps (mobile, edge), tree-shaking everything. **Choose ArkType** for: maximum runtime performance, TypeScript-native feel.

Three Zod methods that modify validation behavior, each for different use cases.

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

// .refine() — simple boolean validation with one error
const evenNumber = z.number().refine(
  n => n % 2 === 0,
  'Must be an even number'
);
// Returns: boolean → single error
// Use for: simple yes/no checks

// .superRefine() — complex validation with multiple errors
const password = z.string().superRefine((val, ctx) => {
  if (val.length < 8) {
    ctx.addIssue({ code: z.ZodIssueCode.too_small, minimum: 8, type: 'string', inclusive: true, message: 'Too short' });
  }
  if (!/[A-Z]/.test(val)) {
    ctx.addIssue({ code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom, message: 'Needs uppercase' });
  }
  if (!/[0-9]/.test(val)) {
    ctx.addIssue({ code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom, message: 'Needs number' });
  }
  // Can add MULTIPLE errors at once
});
// Returns: void (errors via ctx.addIssue)
// Use for: multiple validation rules, custom error codes, conditional errors

// .transform() — change the value (not for validation)
const trimmedLower = z.string()
  .transform(val => val.trim().toLowerCase());
// Returns: the new value
// Use for: data normalization, type conversion

// Combined pattern:
const emailSchema = z.string()
  .email()                    // Built-in validation
  .refine(                    // Simple custom check
    e => !e.endsWith('.test'),
    'Test emails not allowed'
  )
  .transform(                 // Transform the value
    e => e.toLowerCase().trim()
  );
```

| Method | Returns | Multiple errors | Changes value | Changes type |
|--------|---------|-----------------|---------------|---------------|
| .refine() | boolean | No (one error) | No | No |
| .superRefine() | void | Yes (ctx.addIssue) | No | No |
| .transform() | new value | Yes (with ctx) | Yes | Yes |

Order matters: validate first, then refine, then transform. After `.transform()` or `.refine()`, the schema becomes `ZodEffects` and loses `.extend()`, `.pick()`, etc.

Three layers of validation, each catching different classes of errors.

```typescript
// Layer 1: CLIENT-SIDE (UX feedback)
// react-hook-form + Zod
const schema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email('Invalid email'),
  age: z.coerce.number().min(18, 'Must be 18+'),
});
const { register } = useForm({ resolver: zodResolver(schema) });
// Catches: typos, format errors, missing fields
// Bypassed by: curl, Postman, DevTools, disabled JS

// Layer 2: SERVER-SIDE (security boundary)
app.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  const result = schema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!result.success) return res.status(422).json(result.error);
  // Additional checks not possible client-side:
  const existing = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email: result.data.email } });
  if (existing) return res.status(409).json({ error: 'Email taken' });
});
// Catches: all client-bypassed attacks, business logic, uniqueness
// Bypassed by: bugs in validation code, race conditions

// Layer 3: DATABASE CONSTRAINTS (last line of defense)
// Prisma schema:
model User {
  id    String @id @default(uuid())
  email String @unique          // Prevents duplicates even with race conditions
  age   Int                     // Rejects non-integers
  @@index([email])               // Performance
}

// SQL constraints:
ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT check_age CHECK (age >= 18);
ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT unique_email UNIQUE (email);
ALTER TABLE users ALTER COLUMN email SET NOT NULL;
// Catches: race conditions, ORM bugs, direct DB access, migration errors
// Cannot be bypassed (short of DBA access)
```

| Layer | Purpose | Catches | Bypassed by |
|-------|---------|---------|-------------|
| Client | UX feedback | Format errors, typos | curl, DevTools |
| Server | Security | All input attacks, business rules | Code bugs, race conditions |
| Database | Data integrity | Everything above + race conditions | DBA access only |

Never rely on a single layer. Client validation improves UX. Server validation enforces security. Database constraints guarantee integrity. All three are necessary for production applications.

Configure ESLint rules to enforce consistent Zod usage and catch common mistakes.

```typescript
// .eslintrc.js
module.exports = {
  rules: {
    // Enforce safeParse over parse in route handlers
    'no-restricted-syntax': [
      'error',
      {
        selector: "CallExpression[callee.property.name='parse'][callee.object.name=/Schema$/]",
        message: 'Use .safeParse() instead of .parse() in route handlers. .parse() throws on invalid input.',
      },
    ],
  },
};

// Custom ESLint rule (simplified) for enforcing validation middleware:
// Ensure all POST/PUT/PATCH routes have validation
// This would be a custom plugin — here's the concept:

// Instead of ESLint, use TypeScript to enforce validation:
// typed-route.ts
import { z, ZodSchema } from 'zod';

type ValidatedHandler<T> = (data: T) => Promise<Response>;

// Forces you to provide a schema
function post<T>(path: string, schema: ZodSchema<T>, handler: ValidatedHandler<T>) {
  return app.post(path, async (req, res) => {
    const result = schema.safeParse(req.body);
    if (!result.success) {
      return res.status(422).json({ errors: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors });
    }
    return handler(result.data);
  });
}

// Usage — impossible to skip validation
post('/api/users', createUserSchema, async (data) => {
  // data is fully typed and validated
  const user = await db.user.create({ data });
  return Response.json(user, { status: 201 });
});

// This pattern makes unvalidated endpoints a compile-time error,
// not a runtime oversight.
```

The typed route helper is more effective than ESLint rules — it makes validation a structural requirement, not a style convention. Combine with shared schemas from a monorepo package for maximum safety.
